ce:section.ce:para:
The HPU/RZN nanocomposites were fabricated by an in situ polymerization technique (Scheme 2
                        ). The fundamental aspects for the successful nanocomposite preparation are concentration of the reactants, nature and amount of nanohybrid, rate of addition of the branching moiety, temperature reaction and time [19,35]. Consequently, branching unit was added drop-wise at room temperature in a dilute xylene solution (15–20%) to avoid gel formation, in the second step of the reaction. Also, the RCD-ZnO nanohybrid was slowly incorporated in the second step to attain good interfacial interactions with the HPU matrix. Strong interfacial interactions result in better stabilization of nanohybrid within the matrix. FTIR spectra of HPU nanocomposites (Fig. 3
                        a) confirmed the completion of the reaction, where the disappearance of the free –NCO group band at 2270 cm−1 was observed [35]. Further, the FTIR study of the nanocomposites displayed the characteristic bands of HPU. The vibration bands near 1680 are attributed to CO stretching vibration (due to amide I and ester linkage) [36]. Additionally, NH stretching and NH bending vibrations were observed at 3433 cm−1 and 1598 cm−1, respectively. At 2954 cm−1 (asymmetric CH vibration), 2867 cm−1 (symmetric CH vibration), 1062–1093 cm−1 (NH deformation vibration), 1177–1225 cm−1 (CO stretching vibration) and a few characteristic bands for urethane linkage were observed. The increased amount of nanohybrid brought about a shift in the CO band from 1695 cm−1 to 1683 cm−1 in the nanocomposites. This specifies the presence of interactions among the polymer chains and the nanohybrid that increase with an increase in the nanohybrid content [35–37]. Two distinct peaks at 2θ = 21.24 (d-spacing = 0.41 nm) and 23.51 (d-spacing = 0.375 nm) were observed in the XRD patterns of HPU nanocomposites (Fig. 3b), attributed to (1 1 0) and (2 0 0) crystal planes of the PCL moiety present in HPU matrix [35]. The PCL peaks shifted slightly towards a higher angle upon addition of the nanohybrid which may be attributed to the formation of a dense structure of HPU nanocomposite [35,37]. Here, it is pertinent to mention that no such distinct peak is observed for RCD-ZnO in the XRD patterns of the nanocomposites. This may be due to the presence of a very small amount of RCD-ZnO in the nanocomposite (0.5–2.0 wt% of total amount of HPU). The homogeneous distribution of RCD-ZnO nanohybrid within the HPU/RZN matrix was unveiled from bulk morphology investigations by TEM (Fig. 3c–e).

The mechanical performance of the nanocomposites provided notable insights into their quality and applicability. The results demonstrated significant enhancements in most of the mechanical properties of the nanocomposites (Table 1
                        ). Moreover, all the nanocomposites showed loading-dependent enhancement of mechanical properties, even at very low loading percentage (0.5–2.0 wt%). Tensile strength of the nanocomposites magnified up to almost 194% (maximum), displaying a linear increasing trend with percent nanohybrid loading. Elongation at break of the nanocomposites displayed a similar increase up to almost 139% (maximum) in tandem with increasing nanohybrid loading. Simultaneously, the measurement of toughness from stress-strain profiles of the nanocomposites revealed hugely improved values up to almost 354% (maximum) on increasing nanohybrid loading (Fig. 4
                        a). Along the same lines, the nanocomposites exhibited high values of scratch hardness and impact strength, although the precise values could not be calculated as they surpassed the limiting values of the equipments used.
